Instructions

The aim of this experiment is to study how people learn vocabulary in a language they don't know.

In this experiment you will be presented with pairs of vocabulary from an artificial language.

Your task is to memorize which of the pairs are considered a valid pair in the artificial language.

A valid pair could look like this:

urbe tarb

An invalid pair could look like this:

urbe makt


For each pair that is presented to you, you can indicate whether or not you think it is a valid pair.

If you think it is a valid pair, press f.

If you think it is an invalid pair, press j.

After you make your choice, you will be provided with feedback.

You have 3.5 seconds to respond and the feedback will be shown for 2 seconds.

You will encounter each pair 5 times.

The first time you see each pair, you will have to guess whether it is valid or not. With time you should be able to use the knowledge you gain from the feedback after each trial to choose more reasonably.

The more correct answers you give, the more bonus payment you earn. In order to count towards the bonus, responses have to be given within the time limit.

The experiment is divided into two parts. Each part consists of a seperate list of pairs.

Press any key to start with the first list.

Instructions

The aim of this experiment is to study how people learn vocabulary in a language they don't know.

In this experiment you will be presented with pairs of vocabulary from an artificial language.

Your task is to memorize which of the pairs are considered a valid pair in the artificial language.

A valid pair could look like this:

urbe tarb

An invalid pair could look like this:

urbe makt


For each pair that is presented to you, you can indicate whether or not you think it is a valid pair.

If you think it is a valid pair, press f.

If you think it is an invalid pair, press j.

After you make your choice, you will be provided with feedback.

You have 3.5 seconds to respond and the feedback will be shown for 2 seconds.

You will encounter each pair 5 times.

The first time you see each pair, you will have to guess whether it is valid or not. With time you should be able to use the knowledge you gain from the feedback after each trial to choose more reasonably.

The more correct answers you give, the more bonus payment you earn. In order to count towards the bonus, responses have to be given within the time limit.

The experiment is divided into two parts. Each part consists of a seperate list of pairs.

Press any key to start with the first list.

Instructions

The aim of this experiment is to study how people learn vocabulary in a language they don't know.

In this experiment you will be presented with pairs of vocabulary from an artificial language.

Your task is to memorize which of the pairs are considered a valid pair in the artificial language.

A valid pair could look like this:

urbe tarb

An invalid pair could look like this:

urbe makt


For each pair that is presented to you, you can indicate whether or not you think it is a valid pair.

If you think it is a valid pair, press f.

If you think it is an invalid pair, press j.

After you make your choice, you will be provided with feedback.

You have 3.5 seconds to respond and the feedback will be shown for 2 seconds.

You will encounter each pair 5 times.

The first time you see each pair, you will have to guess whether it is valid or not. With time you should be able to use the knowledge you gain from the feedback after each trial to choose more reasonably.

The more correct answers you give, the more bonus payment you earn. In order to count towards the bonus, responses have to be given within the time limit.

The experiment is divided into two parts. Each part consists of a seperate list of pairs.

Press any key to start with the first list.

Instructions

The aim of this experiment is to study how people learn vocabulary in a language they don't know.

In this experiment you will be presented with pairs of vocabulary from an artificial language.

Your task is to memorize which of the pairs are considered a valid pair in the artificial language.

A valid pair could look like this:

urbe tarb

An invalid pair could look like this:

urbe makt


For each pair that is presented to you, you can indicate whether or not you think it is a valid pair.

If you think it is a valid pair, press f.

If you think it is an invalid pair, press j.

After you make your choice, you will be provided with feedback.

You have 3.5 seconds to respond and the feedback will be shown for 2 seconds.

You will encounter each pair 5 times.

The first time you see each pair, you will have to guess whether it is valid or not. With time you should be able to use the knowledge you gain from the feedback after each trial to choose more reasonably.

The more correct answers you give, the more bonus payment you earn. In order to count towards the bonus, responses have to be given within the time limit.

The experiment is divided into two parts. Each part consists of a seperate list of pairs.

Press any key to start with the first list.

Instructions

The aim of this experiment is to study how people learn vocabulary in a language they don't know.

In this experiment you will be presented with pairs of vocabulary from an artificial language.

Your task is to memorize which of the pairs are considered a valid pair in the artificial language.

A valid pair could look like this:

urbe tarb

An invalid pair could look like this:

urbe makt


For each pair that is presented to you, you can indicate whether or not you think it is a valid pair.

If you think it is a valid pair, press f.

If you think it is an invalid pair, press j.

After you make your choice, you will be provided with feedback.

You have 3.5 seconds to respond and the feedback will be shown for 2 seconds.

You will encounter each pair 5 times.

The first time you see each pair, you will have to guess whether it is valid or not. With time you should be able to use the knowledge you gain from the feedback after each trial to choose more reasonably.

The more correct answers you give, the more bonus payment you earn. In order to count towards the bonus, responses have to be given within the time limit.

The experiment is divided into two parts. Each part consists of a seperate list of pairs.

Press any key to start with the first list.

Instructions

The aim of this experiment is to study how people learn vocabulary in a language they don't know.

In this experiment you will be presented with pairs of vocabulary from an artificial language.

Your task is to memorize which of the pairs are considered a valid pair in the artificial language.

A valid pair could look like this:

urbe tarb

An invalid pair could look like this:

urbe makt


For each pair that is presented to you, you can indicate whether or not you think it is a valid pair.

If you think it is a valid pair, press f.

If you think it is an invalid pair, press j.

After you make your choice, you will be provided with feedback.

You have 3.5 seconds to respond and the feedback will be shown for 2 seconds.

You will encounter each pair 5 times.

The first time you see each pair, you will have to guess whether it is valid or not. With time you should be able to use the knowledge you gain from the feedback after each trial to choose more reasonably.

The more correct answers you give, the more bonus payment you earn. In order to count towards the bonus, responses have to be given within the time limit.

The experiment is divided into two parts. Each part consists of a seperate list of pairs.

Press any key to start with the first list.

Instructions

The aim of this experiment is to study how people learn vocabulary in a language they don't know.

In this experiment you will be presented with pairs of vocabulary from an artificial language.

Your task is to memorize which of the pairs are considered a valid pair in the artificial language.

A valid pair could look like this:

urbe tarb

An invalid pair could look like this:

urbe makt


For each pair that is presented to you, you can indicate whether or not you think it is a valid pair.

If you think it is a valid pair, press f.

If you think it is an invalid pair, press j.

After you make your choice, you will be provided with feedback.

You have 3.5 seconds to respond and the feedback will be shown for 2 seconds.

You will encounter each pair 5 times.

The first time you see each pair, you will have to guess whether it is valid or not. With time you should be able to use the knowledge you gain from the feedback after each trial to choose more reasonably.

The more correct answers you give, the more bonus payment you earn. In order to count towards the bonus, responses have to be given within the time limit.

The experiment is divided into two parts. Each part consists of a seperate list of pairs.

Press any key to start with the first list.

Instructions

The aim of this experiment is to study how people learn vocabulary in a language they don't know.

In this experiment you will be presented with pairs of vocabulary from an artificial language.

Your task is to memorize which of the pairs are considered a valid pair in the artificial language.

A valid pair could look like this:

urbe tarb

An invalid pair could look like this:

urbe makt


For each pair that is presented to you, you can indicate whether or not you think it is a valid pair.

If you think it is a valid pair, press f.

If you think it is an invalid pair, press j.

After you make your choice, you will be provided with feedback.

You have 3.5 seconds to respond and the feedback will be shown for 2 seconds.

You will encounter each pair 5 times.

The first time you see each pair, you will have to guess whether it is valid or not. With time you should be able to use the knowledge you gain from the feedback after each trial to choose more reasonably.

The more correct answers you give, the more bonus payment you earn. In order to count towards the bonus, responses have to be given within the time limit.

The experiment is divided into two parts. Each part consists of a seperate list of pairs.

Press any key to start with the first list.

Instructions

The aim of this experiment is to study how people learn vocabulary in a language they don't know.

In this experiment you will be presented with pairs of vocabulary from an artificial language.

Your task is to memorize which of the pairs are considered a valid pair in the artificial language.

A valid pair could look like this:

urbe tarb

An invalid pair could look like this:

urbe makt


For each pair that is presented to you, you can indicate whether or not you think it is a valid pair.

If you think it is a valid pair, press f.

If you think it is an invalid pair, press j.

After you make your choice, you will be provided with feedback.

You have 3.5 seconds to respond and the feedback will be shown for 2 seconds.

You will encounter each pair 5 times.

The first time you see each pair, you will have to guess whether it is valid or not. With time you should be able to use the knowledge you gain from the feedback after each trial to choose more reasonably.

The more correct answers you give, the more bonus payment you earn. In order to count towards the bonus, responses have to be given within the time limit.

The experiment is divided into two parts. Each part consists of a seperate list of pairs.

Press any key to start with the first list.

Instructions

The aim of this experiment is to study how people learn vocabulary in a language they don't know.

In this experiment you will be presented with pairs of vocabulary from an artificial language.

Your task is to memorize which of the pairs are considered a valid pair in the artificial language.

A valid pair could look like this:

urbe tarb

An invalid pair could look like this:

urbe makt


For each pair that is presented to you, you can indicate whether or not you think it is a valid pair.

If you think it is a valid pair, press f.

If you think it is an invalid pair, press j.

After you make your choice, you will be provided with feedback.

You have 3.5 seconds to respond and the feedback will be shown for 2 seconds.

You will encounter each pair 5 times.

The first time you see each pair, you will have to guess whether it is valid or not. With time you should be able to use the knowledge you gain from the feedback after each trial to choose more reasonably.

The more correct answers you give, the more bonus payment you earn. In order to count towards the bonus, responses have to be given within the time limit.

The experiment is divided into two parts. Each part consists of a seperate list of pairs.

Press any key to start with the first list.

The aim of this experiment is to study how people learn vocabulary in a language they don't know.

In this experiment you will be presented with pairs of vocabulary from an artificial language.

Your task is to memorize which of the pairs are considered a valid pair in the artificial language.

A valid pair could look like this:

urbe tarb

An invalid pair could look like this:

urbe makt


For each pair that is presented to you, you can indicate whether or not you think it is a valid pair.

If you think it is a valid pair, press f.

If you think it is an invalid pair, press j.

After you make your choice, you will be provided with feedback.

You have 3.5 seconds to respond and the feedback will be shown for 2 seconds.

You will encounter each pair 5 times.

The first time you see each pair, you will have to guess whether it is valid or not. With time you should be able to use the knowledge you gain from the feedback after each trial to choose more reasonably.

The more correct answers you give, the more bonus payment you earn. In order to count towards the bonus, responses have to be given within the time limit.

The experiment is divided into two parts. Each part consists of a seperate list of pairs.

Press any key to start with the first list.

Instructions

The aim of this experiment is to study how people learn vocabulary in a language they don't know.

In this experiment you will be presented with pairs of vocabulary from an artificial language.

Your task is to memorize which of the pairs are considered a valid pair in the artificial language.

A valid pair could look like this:

urbe tarb

An invalid pair could look like this:

urbe makt


For each pair that is presented to you, you can indicate whether or not you think it is a valid pair.

If you think it is a valid pair, press f.

If you think it is an invalid pair, press j.

After you make your choice, you will be provided with feedback.

You have 3.5 seconds to respond and the feedback will be shown for 2 seconds.

You will encounter each pair 5 times.

The first time you see each pair, you will have to guess whether it is valid or not. With time you should be able to use the knowledge you gain from the feedback after each trial to choose more reasonably.

The more correct answers you give, the more bonus payment you earn. In order to count towards the bonus, responses have to be given within the time limit.

The experiment is divided into two parts. Each part consists of a seperate list of pairs.

Press any key to start with the first list.

Instructions

The aim of this experiment is to study how people learn vocabulary in a language they don't know.

In this experiment you will be presented with pairs of vocabulary from an artificial language.

Your task is to memorize which of the pairs are considered a valid pair in the artificial language.

A valid pair could look like this:

urbe tarb

An invalid pair could look like this:

urbe makt


For each pair that is presented to you, you can indicate whether or not you think it is a valid pair.

If you think it is a valid pair, press f.

If you think it is an invalid pair, press j.

After you make your choice, you will be provided with feedback.

You have 3.5 seconds to respond and the feedback will be shown for 2 seconds.

You will encounter each pair 5 times.

The first time you see each pair, you will have to guess whether it is valid or not. With time you should be able to use the knowledge you gain from the feedback after each trial to choose more reasonably.

The more correct answers you give, the more bonus payment you earn. In order to count towards the bonus, responses have to be given within the time limit.

The experiment is divided into two parts. Each part consists of a seperate list of pairs.

Press any key to start with the first list.

Instructions

The aim of this experiment is to study how people learn vocabulary in a language they don't know.

In this experiment you will be presented with pairs of vocabulary from an artificial language.

Your task is to memorize which of the pairs are considered a valid pair in the artificial language.

A valid pair could look like this:

urbe tarb

An invalid pair could look like this:

urbe makt


For each pair that is presented to you, you can indicate whether or not you think it is a valid pair.

If you think it is a valid pair, press f.

If you think it is an invalid pair, press j.

After you make your choice, you will be provided with feedback.

You have 3.5 seconds to respond and the feedback will be shown for 2 seconds.

You will encounter each pair 5 times.

The first time you see each pair, you will have to guess whether it is valid or not. With time you should be able to use the knowledge you gain from the feedback after each trial to choose more reasonably.

The more correct answers you give, the more bonus payment you earn. In order to count towards the bonus, responses have to be given within the time limit.

The experiment is divided into two parts. Each part consists of a seperate list of pairs.

Press any key to start with the first list.

Instructions

The aim of this experiment is to study how people learn vocabulary in a language they don't know.

In this experiment you will be presented with pairs of vocabulary from an artificial language.

Your task is to memorize which of the pairs are considered a valid pair in the artificial language.

A valid pair could look like this:

urbe tarb

An invalid pair could look like this:

urbe makt


For each pair that is presented to you, you can indicate whether or not you think it is a valid pair.

If you think it is a valid pair, press f.

If you think it is an invalid pair, press j.

After you make your choice, you will be provided with feedback.

You have 3.5 seconds to respond and the feedback will be shown for 2 seconds.

You will encounter each pair 5 times.

The first time you see each pair, you will have to guess whether it is valid or not. With time you should be able to use the knowledge you gain from the feedback after each trial to choose more reasonably.

The more correct answers you give, the more bonus payment you earn. In order to count towards the bonus, responses have to be given within the time limit.

Instructions

The aim of this experiment is to study how people learn vocabulary in a language they don't know.

In this experiment you will be presented with pairs of vocabulary from an artificial language.

Your task is to memorize which of the pairs are considered a valid pair in the artificial language.

A valid pair could look like this:

urbe tarb

An invalid pair could look like this:

urbe makt


For each pair that is presented to you, you can indicate whether or not you think it is a valid pair.

If you think it is a valid pair, press f.

If you think it is an invalid pair, press j.

After you make your choice, you will be provided with feedback.

You have 3.5 seconds to respond and the feedback will be shown for 2 seconds.

You will encounter each pair 5 times.

The first time you see each pair, you will have to guess whether it is valid or not. With time you should be able to use the knowledge you gain from the feedback after each trial to choose more reasonably.

The more correct answers you give, the more bonus payment you earn. In order to count towards the bonus, responses have to be given within the time limit.

The experiment is divided into two parts. Each part consists of a seperate list of pairs.

Press any key to start with the first list.

Instructions

The aim of this experiment is to study how people learn vocabulary in a language they don't know.

In this experiment you will be presented with pairs of vocabulary from an artificial language.

Your task is to memorize which of the pairs are considered a valid pair in the artificial language.

A valid pair could look like this:

urbe tarb

An invalid pair could look like this:

urbe makt


For each pair that is presented to you, you can indicate whether or not you think it is a valid pair.

If you think it is a valid pair, press f.

If you think it is an invalid pair, press j.

After you make your choice, you will be provided with feedback.

You have 3.5 seconds to respond and the feedback will be shown for 2 seconds.

You will encounter each pair 5 times.

The first time you see each pair, you will have to guess whether it is valid or not. With time you should be able to use the knowledge you gain from the feedback after each trial to choose more reasonably.

The more correct answers you give, the more bonus payment you earn. In order to count towards the bonus, responses have to be given within the time limit.

The experiment is divided into two parts. Each part consists of a seperate list of pairs.

Press any key to start with the first list.

Instructions

The aim of this experiment is to study how people learn vocabulary in a language they don't know.

In this experiment you will be presented with pairs of vocabulary from an artificial language.

Your task is to memorize which of the pairs are considered a valid pair in the artificial language.

A valid pair could look like this:

urbe tarb

An invalid pair could look like this:

urbe makt


For each pair that is presented to you, you can indicate whether or not you think it is a valid pair.

If you think it is a valid pair, press f.

If you think it is an invalid pair, press j.

After you make your choice, you will be provided with feedback.

You have 3.5 seconds to respond and the feedback will be shown for 2 seconds.

You will encounter each pair 5 times.

The first time you see each pair, you will have to guess whether it is valid or not. With time you should be able to use the knowledge you gain from the feedback after each trial to choose more reasonably.

The more correct answers you give, the more bonus payment you earn. In order to count towards the bonus, responses have to be given within the time limit.

The experiment is divided into two parts. Each part consists of a seperate list of pairs.

Press any key to start with the first list.

Instructions

The aim of this experiment is to study how people learn vocabulary in a language they don't know.

In this experiment you will be presented with pairs of vocabulary from an artificial language.

Your task is to memorize which of the pairs are considered a valid pair in the artificial language.

A valid pair could look like this:

urbe tarb

An invalid pair could look like this:

urbe makt


For each pair that is presented to you, you can indicate whether or not you think it is a valid pair.

If you think it is a valid pair, press f.

If you think it is an invalid pair, press j.

After you make your choice, you will be provided with feedback.

You have 3.5 seconds to respond and the feedback will be shown for 2 seconds.

You will encounter each pair 5 times.

The first time you see each pair, you will have to guess whether it is valid or not. With time you should be able to use the knowledge you gain from the feedback after each trial to choose more reasonably.

The more correct answers you give, the more bonus payment you earn. In order to count towards the bonus, responses have to be given within the time limit.

The experiment is divided into two parts. Each part consists of a seperate list of pairs.

Press any key to start with the first list.

Instructions

The aim of this experiment is to study how people learn vocabulary in a language they don't know.

In this experiment you will be presented with pairs of vocabulary from an artificial language.

Your task is to memorize which of the pairs are considered a valid pair in the artificial language.

A valid pair could look like this:

urbe tarb

An invalid pair could look like this:

urbe makt


For each pair that is presented to you, you can indicate whether or not you think it is a valid pair.

If you think it is a valid pair, press f.

If you think it is an invalid pair, press j.

After you make your choice, you will be provided with feedback.

You have 3.5 seconds to respond and the feedback will be shown for 2 seconds.

You will encounter each pair 5 times.

The first time you see each pair, you will have to guess whether it is valid or not. With time you should be able to use the knowledge you gain from the feedback after each trial to choose more reasonably.

The more correct answers you give, the more bonus payment you earn. In order to count towards the bonus, responses have to be given within the time limit.

The experiment is divided into two parts. Each part consists of a seperate list of pairs.

Press any key to start with the first list.

Instructions

The aim of this experiment is to study how people learn vocabulary in a language they don't know.

In this experiment you will be presented with pairs of vocabulary from an artificial language.

Your task is to memorize which of the pairs are considered a valid pair in the artificial language.

A valid pair could look like this:

urbe tarb

An invalid pair could look like this:

urbe makt


For each pair that is presented to you, you can indicate whether or not you think it is a valid pair.

If you think it is a valid pair, press f.

If you think it is an invalid pair, press j.

After you make your choice, you will be provided with feedback.

You have 3.5 seconds to respond and the feedback will be shown for 2 seconds.

You will encounter each pair 5 times.

The first time you see each pair, you will have to guess whether it is valid or not. With time you should be able to use the knowledge you gain from the feedback after each trial to choose more reasonably.

The more correct answers you give, the more bonus payment you earn. In order to count towards the bonus, responses have to be given within the time limit.

The experiment is divided into two parts. Each part consists of a seperate list of pairs.

Press any key to start with the first list.

Instructions

The aim of this experiment is to study how people learn vocabulary in a language they don't know.

In this experiment you will be presented with pairs of vocabulary from an artificial language.

Your task is to memorize which of the pairs are considered a valid pair in the artificial language.

A valid pair could look like this:

urbe tarb

An invalid pair could look like this:

urbe makt


For each pair that is presented to you, you can indicate whether or not you think it is a valid pair.

If you think it is a valid pair, press f.

If you think it is an invalid pair, press j.

After you make your choice, you will be provided with feedback.

You have 3.5 seconds to respond and the feedback will be shown for 2 seconds.

You will encounter each pair 5 times.

The first time you see each pair, you will have to guess whether it is valid or not. With time you should be able to use the knowledge you gain from the feedback after each trial to choose more reasonably.

The more correct answers you give, the more bonus payment you earn. In order to count towards the bonus, responses have to be given within the time limit.

The experiment is divided into two parts. Each part consists of a seperate list of pairs.

Press any key to start with the first list.

Instructions

The aim of this experiment is to study how people learn vocabulary in a language they don't know.

In this experiment you will be presented with pairs of vocabulary from an artificial language.

Your task is to memorize which of the pairs are considered a valid pair in the artificial language.

A valid pair could look like this:

urbe tarb

An invalid pair could look like this:

urbe makt


For each pair that is presented to you, you can indicate whether or not you think it is a valid pair.

If you think it is a valid pair, press f.

If you think it is an invalid pair, press j.

After you make your choice, you will be provided with feedback.

You have 3.5 seconds to respond and the feedback will be shown for 2 seconds.

You will encounter each pair 5 times.

The first time you see each pair, you will have to guess whether it is valid or not. With time you should be able to use the knowledge you gain from the feedback after each trial to choose more reasonably.

The more correct answers you give, the more bonus payment you earn. In order to count towards the bonus, responses have to be given within the time limit.

The experiment is divided into two parts. Each part consists of a seperate list of pairs.

Press any key to start with the first list.

Instructions

The aim of this experiment is to study how people learn vocabulary in a language they don't know.

In this experiment you will be presented with pairs of vocabulary from an artificial language.

Your task is to memorize which of the pairs are considered a valid pair in the artificial language.

A valid pair could look like this:

urbe tarb

An invalid pair could look like this:

urbe makt


For each pair that is presented to you, you can indicate whether or not you think it is a valid pair.

If you think it is a valid pair, press f.

If you think it is an invalid pair, press j.

After you make your choice, you will be provided with feedback.

You have 3.5 seconds to respond and the feedback will be shown for 2 seconds.

You will encounter each pair 5 times.

The first time you see each pair, you will have to guess whether it is valid or not. With time you should be able to use the knowledge you gain from the feedback after each trial to choose more reasonably.

The more correct answers you give, the more bonus payment you earn. In order to count towards the bonus, responses have to be given within the time limit.

The experiment is divided into two parts. Each part consists of a seperate list of pairs.

Press any key to start with the first list.

Instructions

The aim of this experiment is to study how people learn vocabulary in a language they don't know.

In this experiment you will be presented with pairs of vocabulary from an artificial language.

Your task is to memorize which of the pairs are considered a valid pair in the artificial language.

A valid pair could look like this:

urbe tarb

An invalid pair could look like this:

urbe makt


For each pair that is presented to you, you can indicate whether or not you think it is a valid pair.

If you think it is a valid pair, press f.

If you think it is an invalid pair, press j.

After you make your choice, you will be provided with feedback.

You have 3.5 seconds to respond and the feedback will be shown for 2 seconds.

You will encounter each pair 5 times.

The first time you see each pair, you will have to guess whether it is valid or not. With time you should be able to use the knowledge you gain from the feedback after each trial to choose more reasonably.

The more correct answers you give, the more bonus payment you earn. In order to count towards the bonus, responses have to be given within the time limit.

The experiment is divided into two parts. Each part consists of a seperate list of pairs.

Press any key to start with the first list.

Instructions

The aim of this experiment is to study how people learn vocabulary in a language they don't know.

In this experiment you will be presented with pairs of vocabulary from an artificial language.

Your task is to memorize which of the pairs are considered a valid pair in the artificial language.

A valid pair could look like this:

urbe tarb

An invalid pair could look like this:

urbe makt


For each pair that is presented to you, you can indicate whether or not you think it is a valid pair.

If you think it is a valid pair, press f.

If you think it is an invalid pair, press j.

After you make your choice, you will be provided with feedback.

You have 3.5 seconds to respond and the feedback will be shown for 2 seconds.

You will encounter each pair 5 times.

The first time you see each pair, you will have to guess whether it is valid or not. With time you should be able to use the knowledge you gain from the feedback after each trial to choose more reasonably.

The more correct answers you give, the more bonus payment you earn. In order to count towards the bonus, responses have to be given within the time limit.

The experiment is divided into two parts. Each part consists of a seperate list of pairs.

Press any key to start with the first list.

Instructions

The aim of this experiment is to study how people learn vocabulary in a language they don't know.

In this experiment you will be presented with pairs of vocabulary from an artificial language.

Your task is to memorize which of the pairs are considered a valid pair in the artificial language.

A valid pair could look like this:

urbe tarb

An invalid pair could look like this:

urbe makt


For each pair that is presented to you, you can indicate whether or not you think it is a valid pair.

If you think it is a valid pair, press f.

If you think it is an invalid pair, press j.

After you make your choice, you will be provided with feedback.

You have 3.5 seconds to respond and the feedback will be shown for 2 seconds.

You will encounter each pair 5 times.

The first time you see each pair, you will have to guess whether it is valid or not. With time you should be able to use the knowledge you gain from the feedback after each trial to choose more reasonably.

The more correct answers you give, the more bonus payment you earn. In order to count towards the bonus, responses have to be given within the time limit.

The experiment is divided into two parts. Each part consists of a seperate list of pairs.

Press any key to start with the first list.

Instructions

The aim of this experiment is to study how people learn vocabulary in a language they don't know.

In this experiment you will be presented with pairs of vocabulary from an artificial language.

Your task is to memorize which of the pairs are considered a valid pair in the artificial language.

A valid pair could look like this:

urbe tarb

An invalid pair could look like this:

urbe makt


For each pair that is presented to you, you can indicate whether or not you think it is a valid pair.

If you think it is a valid pair, press f.

If you think it is an invalid pair, press j.

After you make your choice, you will be provided with feedback.

You have 3.5 seconds to respond and the feedback will be shown for 2 seconds.

You will encounter each pair 5 times.

Instructions

The aim of this experiment is to study how people learn vocabulary in a language they don't know.

In this experiment you will be presented with pairs of vocabulary from an artificial language.

Your task is to memorize which of the pairs are considered a valid pair in the artificial language.

A valid pair could look like this:

urbe tarb

An invalid pair could look like this:

urbe makt


For each pair that is presented to you, you can indicate whether or not you think it is a valid pair.

If you think it is a valid pair, press f.

If you think it is an invalid pair, press j.

After you make your choice, you will be provided with feedback.

You have 3.5 seconds to respond and the feedback will be shown for 2 seconds.

You will encounter each pair 5 times.

The first time you see each pair, you will have to guess whether it is valid or not. With time you should be able to use the knowledge you gain from the feedback after each trial to choose more reasonably.

The more correct answers you give, the more bonus payment you earn. In order to count towards the bonus, responses have to be given within the time limit.

The experiment is divided into two parts. Each part consists of a seperate list of pairs.

Press any key to start with the first list.

Instructions

The aim of this experiment is to study how people learn vocabulary in a language they don't know.

In this experiment you will be presented with pairs of vocabulary from an artificial language.

Your task is to memorize which of the pairs are considered a valid pair in the artificial language.

A valid pair could look like this:

urbe tarb

An invalid pair could look like this:

urbe makt


For each pair that is presented to you, you can indicate whether or not you think it is a valid pair.

If you think it is a valid pair, press f.

If you think it is an invalid pair, press j.

After you make your choice, you will be provided with feedback.

You have 3.5 seconds to respond and the feedback will be shown for 2 seconds.

You will encounter each pair 5 times.

The first time you see each pair, you will have to guess whether it is valid or not. With time you should be able to use the knowledge you gain from the feedback after each trial to choose more reasonably.

The more correct answers you give, the more bonus payment you earn. In order to count towards the bonus, responses have to be given within the time limit.

The experiment is divided into two parts. Each part consists of a seperate list of pairs.

Press any key to start with the first list.

Instructions

The aim of this experiment is to study how people learn vocabulary in a language they don't know.

In this experiment you will be presented with pairs of vocabulary from an artificial language.

Your task is to memorize which of the pairs are considered a valid pair in the artificial language.

A valid pair could look like this:

urbe tarb

An invalid pair could look like this:

urbe makt


For each pair that is presented to you, you can indicate whether or not you think it is a valid pair.

If you think it is a valid pair, press f.

If you think it is an invalid pair, press j.

After you make your choice, you will be provided with feedback.

You have 3.5 seconds to respond and the feedback will be shown for 2 seconds.

You will encounter each pair 5 times.

The first time you see each pair, you will have to guess whether it is valid or not. With time you should be able to use the knowledge you gain from the feedback after each trial to choose more reasonably.

The more correct answers you give, the more bonus payment you earn. In order to count towards the bonus, responses have to be given within the time limit.

The experiment is divided into two parts. Each part consists of a seperate list of pairs.

Press any key to start with the first list.

Instructions

The aim of this experiment is to study how people learn vocabulary in a language they don't know.

In this experiment you will be presented with pairs of vocabulary from an artificial language.

Your task is to memorize which of the pairs are considered a valid pair in the artificial language.

A valid pair could look like this:

urbe tarb

An invalid pair could look like this:

urbe makt


For each pair that is presented to you, you can indicate whether or not you think it is a valid pair.

If you think it is a valid pair, press f.

If you think it is an invalid pair, press j.

After you make your choice, you will be provided with feedback.

You have 3.5 seconds to respond and the feedback will be shown for 2 seconds.

You will encounter each pair 5 times.

The first time you see each pair, you will have to guess whether it is valid or not. With time you should be able to use the knowledge you gain from the feedback after each trial to choose more reasonably.

The more correct answers you give, the more bonus payment you earn. In order to count towards the bonus, responses have to be given within the time limit.

The experiment is divided into two parts. Each part consists of a seperate list of pairs.

Press any key to start with the first list.

Instructions

The aim of this experiment is to study how people learn vocabulary in a language they don't know.

In this experiment you will be presented with pairs of vocabulary from an artificial language.

Your task is to memorize which of the pairs are considered a valid pair in the artificial language.

A valid pair could look like this:

urbe tarb

An invalid pair could look like this:

urbe makt


For each pair that is presented to you, you can indicate whether or not you think it is a valid pair.

If you think it is a valid pair, press f.

If you think it is an invalid pair, press j.

After you make your choice, you will be provided with feedback.

You have 3.5 seconds to respond and the feedback will be shown for 2 seconds.

You will encounter each pair 5 times.

The first time you see each pair, you will have to guess whether it is valid or not. With time you should be able to use the knowledge you gain from the feedback after each trial to choose more reasonably.

The more correct answers you give, the more bonus payment you earn. In order to count towards the bonus, responses have to be given within the time limit.

The experiment is divided into two parts. Each part consists of a seperate list of pairs.

Press any key to start with the first list.

Instructions

The aim of this experiment is to study how people learn vocabulary in a language they don't know.

In this experiment you will be presented with pairs of vocabulary from an artificial language.

Your task is to memorize which of the pairs are considered a valid pair in the artificial language.

A valid pair could look like this:

urbe tarb

An invalid pair could look like this:

urbe makt


For each pair that is presented to you, you can indicate whether or not you think it is a valid pair.

If you think it is a valid pair, press f.

If you think it is an invalid pair, press j.

After you make your choice, you will be provided with feedback.

You have 3.5 seconds to respond and the feedback will be shown for 2 seconds.

You will encounter each pair 5 times.

The first time you see each pair, you will have to guess whether it is valid or not. With time you should be able to use the knowledge you gain from the feedback after each trial to choose more reasonably.

The more correct answers you give, the more bonus payment you earn. In order to count towards the bonus, responses have to be given within the time limit.

The experiment is divided into two parts. Each part consists of a seperate list of pairs.

Press any key to start with the first list.

Instructions

The aim of this experiment is to study how people learn vocabulary in a language they don't know.

In this experiment you will be presented with pairs of vocabulary from an artificial language.

Your task is to memorize which of the pairs are considered a valid pair in the artificial language.

A valid pair could look like this:

urbe tarb

An invalid pair could look like this:

urbe makt


For each pair that is presented to you, you can indicate whether or not you think it is a valid pair.

If you think it is a valid pair, press f.

If you think it is an invalid pair, press j.

After you make your choice, you will be provided with feedback.

You have 3.5 seconds to respond and the feedback will be shown for 2 seconds.

You will encounter each pair 5 times.

The first time you see each pair, you will have to guess whether it is valid or not. With time you should be able to use the knowledge you gain from the feedback after each trial to choose more reasonably.

The more correct answers you give, the more bonus payment you earn. In order to count towards the bonus, responses have to be given within the time limit.

The experiment is divided into two parts. Each part consists of a seperate list of pairs.

Press any key to start with the first list.

Instructions

The aim of this experiment is to study how people learn vocabulary in a language they don't know.

In this experiment you will be presented with pairs of vocabulary from an artificial language.

Your task is to memorize which of the pairs are considered a valid pair in the artificial language.

A valid pair could look like this:

urbe tarb

An invalid pair could look like this:

urbe makt


For each pair that is presented to you, you can indicate whether or not you think it is a valid pair.

If you think it is a valid pair, press f.

If you think it is an invalid pair, press j.

After you make your choice, you will be provided with feedback.

You have 3.5 seconds to respond and the feedback will be shown for 2 seconds.

You will encounter each pair 5 times.

The first time you see each pair, you will have to guess whether it is valid or not. With time you should be able to use the knowledge you gain from the feedback after each trial to choose more reasonably.

The more correct answers you give, the more bonus payment you earn. In order to count towards the bonus, responses have to be given within the time limit.

The experiment is divided into two parts. Each part consists of a seperate list of pairs.

Press any key to start with the first list.

Instructions

The aim of this experiment is to study how people learn vocabulary in a language they don't know.

In this experiment you will be presented with pairs of vocabulary from an artificial language.

Your task is to memorize which of the pairs are considered a valid pair in the artificial language.

A valid pair could look like this:

urbe tarb

An invalid pair could look like this:

urbe makt


For each pair that is presented to you, you can indicate whether or not you think it is a valid pair.

If you think it is a valid pair, press f.

If you think it is an invalid pair, press j.

After you make your choice, you will be provided with feedback.

You have 3.5 seconds to respond and the feedback will be shown for 2 seconds.

You will encounter each pair 5 times.

The first time you see each pair, you will have to guess whether it is valid or not. With time you should be able to use the knowledge you gain from the feedback after each trial to choose more reasonably.

The more correct answers you give, the more bonus payment you earn. In order to count towards the bonus, responses have to be given within the time limit.

The experiment is divided into two parts. Each part consists of a seperate list of pairs.

Press any key to start with the first list.

Instructions

The aim of this experiment is to study how people learn vocabulary in a language they don't know.

In this experiment you will be presented with pairs of vocabulary from an artificial language.

Your task is to memorize which of the pairs are considered a valid pair in the artificial language.

A valid pair could look like this:

urbe tarb

An invalid pair could look like this:

urbe makt


For each pair that is presented to you, you can indicate whether or not you think it is a valid pair.

If you think it is a valid pair, press f.

If you think it is an invalid pair, press j.

After you make your choice, you will be provided with feedback.

You have 3.5 seconds to respond and the feedback will be shown for 2 seconds.

You will encounter each pair 5 times.

The first time you see each pair, you will have to guess whether it is valid or not. With time you should be able to use the knowledge you gain from the feedback after each trial to choose more reasonably.

The more correct answers you give, the more bonus payment you earn. In order to count towards the bonus, responses have to be given within the time limit.

The experiment is divided into two parts. Each part consists of a seperate list of pairs.

Press any key to start with the first list.

Instructions

The aim of this experiment is to study how people learn vocabulary in a language they don't know.

In this experiment you will be presented with pairs of vocabulary from an artificial language.

Your task is to memorize which of the pairs are considered a valid pair in the artificial language.

A valid pair could look like this:

urbe tarb

An invalid pair could look like this:

urbe makt


For each pair that is presented to you, you can indicate whether or not you think it is a valid pair.

If you think it is a valid pair, press f.

If you think it is an invalid pair, press j.

After you make your choice, you will be provided with feedback.

You have 3.5 seconds to respond and the feedback will be shown for 2 seconds.

You will encounter each pair 5 times.

The first time you see each pair, you will have to guess whether it is valid or not. With time you should be able to use the knowledge you gain from the feedback after each trial to choose more reasonably.

The more correct answers you give, the more bonus payment you earn. In order to count towards the bonus, responses have to be given within the time limit.

The experiment is divided into two parts. Each part consists of a seperate list of pairs.

Press any key to start with the first list.

Instructions

The aim of this experiment is to study how people learn vocabulary in a language they don't know.

In this experiment you will be presented with pairs of vocabulary from an artificial language.

Your task is to memorize which of the pairs are considered a valid pair in the artificial language.

A valid pair could look like this:

urbe tarb

An invalid pair could look like this:

urbe makt


For each pair that is presented to you, you can indicate whether or not you think it is a valid pair.

If you think it is a valid pair, press f.

If you think it is an invalid pair, press j.

After you make your choice, you will be provided with feedback.

You have 3.5 seconds to respond and the feedback will be shown for 2 seconds.

You will encounter each pair 5 times.

The first time you see each pair, you will have to guess whether it is valid or not. With time you should be able to use the knowledge you gain from the feedback after each trial to choose more reasonably.

The more correct answers you give, the more bonus payment you earn. In order to count towards the bonus, responses have to be given within the time limit.

The experiment is divided into two parts. Each part consists of a seperate list of pairs.

Press any key to start with the first list.

Instructions

The aim of this experiment is to study how people learn vocabulary in a language they don't know.

In this experiment you will be presented with pairs of vocabulary from an artificial language.

Your task is to memorize which of the pairs are considered a valid pair in the artificial language.

A valid pair could look like this:

urbe tarb

An invalid pair could look like this:

urbe makt


For each pair that is presented to you, you can indicate whether or not you think it is a valid pair.

If you think it is a valid pair, press f.

If you think it is an invalid pair, press j.

After you make your choice, you will be provided with feedback.

You have 3.5 seconds to respond and the feedback will be shown for 2 seconds.

You will encounter each pair 5 times.

The first time you see each pair, you will have to guess whether it is valid or not. With time you should be able to use the knowledge you gain from the feedback after each trial to choose more reasonably.

The more correct answers you give, the more bonus payment you earn. In order to count towards the bonus, responses have to be given within the time limit.

The experiment is divided into two parts. Each part consists of a seperate list of pairs.

Press any key to start with the first list.

Instructions

The aim of this experiment is to study how people learn vocabulary in a language they don't know.

In this experiment you will be presented with pairs of vocabulary from an artificial language.

Your task is to memorize which of the pairs are considered a valid pair in the artificial language.

A valid pair could look like this:

urbe tarb

An invalid pair could look like this:

urbe makt


For each pair that is presented to you, you can indicate whether or not you think it is a valid pair.

If you think it is a valid pair, press f.

If you think it is an invalid pair, press j.

After you make your choice, you will be provided with feedback.

You have 3.5 seconds to respond and the feedback will be shown for 2 seconds.

You will encounter each pair 5 times.

The first time you see each pair, you will have to guess whether it is valid or not. With time you should be able to use the knowledge you gain from the feedback after each trial to choose more reasonably.

The more correct answers you give, the more bonus payment you earn. In order to count towards the bonus, responses have to be given within the time limit.

The experiment is divided into two parts. Each part consists of a seperate list of pairs.

Press any key to start with the first list.

Instructions

The aim of this experiment is to study how people learn vocabulary in a language they don't know.

In this experiment you will be presented with pairs of vocabulary from an artificial language.

Your task is to memorize which of the pairs are considered a valid pair in the artificial language.

A valid pair could look like this:

urbe tarb

An invalid pair could look like this:

urbe makt


For each pair that is presented to you, you can indicate whether or not you think it is a valid pair.

If you think it is a valid pair, press f.

If you think it is an invalid pair, press j.

After you make your choice, you will be provided with feedback.

You have 3.5 seconds to respond and the feedback will be shown for 2 seconds.

You will encounter each pair 5 times.

The first time you see each pair, you will have to guess whether it is valid or not. With time you should be able to use the knowledge you gain from the feedback after each trial to choose more reasonably.

The more correct answers you give, the more bonus payment you earn. In order to count towards the bonus, responses have to be given within the time limit.

The experiment is divided into two parts. Each part consists of a seperate list of pairs.

Press any key to start with the first list.

Instructions

The aim of this experiment is to study how people learn vocabulary in a language they don't know.

In this experiment you will be presented with pairs of vocabulary from an artificial language.

Your task is to memorize which of the pairs are considered a valid pair in the artificial language.

A valid pair could look like this:

urbe tarb

An invalid pair could look like this:

urbe makt


For each pair that is presented to you, you can indicate whether or not you think it is a valid pair.

If you think it is a valid pair, press f.

If you think it is an invalid pair, press j.

After you make your choice, you will be provided with feedback.

You have 3.5 seconds to respond and the feedback will be shown for 2 seconds.

You will encounter each pair 5 times.

The first time you see each pair, you will have to guess whether it is valid or not. With time you should be able to use the knowledge you gain from the feedback after each trial to choose more reasonably.

The more correct answers you give, the more bonus payment you earn. In order to count towards the bonus, responses have to be given within the time limit.

The experiment is divided into two parts. Each part consists of a seperate list of pairs.

Press any key to start with the first list.

Instructions

The aim of this experiment is to study how people learn vocabulary in a language they don't know.

In this experiment you will be presented with pairs of vocabulary from an artificial language.

Your task is to memorize which of the pairs are considered a valid pair in the artificial language.

A valid pair could look like this:

urbe tarb

An invalid pair could look like this:

urbe makt


For each pair that is presented to you, you can indicate whether or not you think it is a valid pair.

If you think it is a valid pair, press f.

If you think it is an invalid pair, press j.

After you make your choice, you will be provided with feedback.

Instructions

The aim of this experiment is to study how people learn vocabulary in a language they don't know.

In this experiment you will be presented with pairs of vocabulary from an artificial language.

Your task is to memorize which of the pairs are considered a valid pair in the artificial language.

A valid pair could look like this:

urbe tarb

An invalid pair could look like this:

urbe makt


For each pair that is presented to you, you can indicate whether or not you think it is a valid pair.

If you think it is a valid pair, press f.

If you think it is an invalid pair, press j.

After you make your choice, you will be provided with feedback.

You have 3.5 seconds to respond and the feedback will be shown for 2 seconds.

You will encounter each pair 5 times.

The first time you see each pair, you will have to guess whether it is valid or not. With time you should be able to use the knowledge you gain from the feedback after each trial to choose more reasonably.

The more correct answers you give, the more bonus payment you earn. In order to count towards the bonus, responses have to be given within the time limit.

The experiment is divided into two parts. Each part consists of a seperate list of pairs.

Press any key to start with the first list.

Instructions

The aim of this experiment is to study how people learn vocabulary in a language they don't know.

In this experiment you will be presented with pairs of vocabulary from an artificial language.

Your task is to memorize which of the pairs are considered a valid pair in the artificial language.

A valid pair could look like this:

urbe tarb

An invalid pair could look like this:

urbe makt


For each pair that is presented to you, you can indicate whether or not you think it is a valid pair.

If you think it is a valid pair, press f.

If you think it is an invalid pair, press j.

After you make your choice, you will be provided with feedback.

You have 3.5 seconds to respond and the feedback will be shown for 2 seconds.

You will encounter each pair 5 times.

The first time you see each pair, you will have to guess whether it is valid or not. With time you should be able to use the knowledge you gain from the feedback after each trial to choose more reasonably.

The more correct answers you give, the more bonus payment you earn. In order to count towards the bonus, responses have to be given within the time limit.

The experiment is divided into two parts. Each part consists of a seperate list of pairs.

Press any key to start with the first list.

Instructions

The aim of this experiment is to study how people learn vocabulary in a language they don't know.

In this experiment you will be presented with pairs of vocabulary from an artificial language.

Your task is to memorize which of the pairs are considered a valid pair in the artificial language.

A valid pair could look like this:

urbe tarb

An invalid pair could look like this:

urbe makt


For each pair that is presented to you, you can indicate whether or not you think it is a valid pair.

If you think it is a valid pair, press f.

If you think it is an invalid pair, press j.

After you make your choice, you will be provided with feedback.

You have 3.5 seconds to respond and the feedback will be shown for 2 seconds.

You will encounter each pair 5 times.

The first time you see each pair, you will have to guess whether it is valid or not. With time you should be able to use the knowledge you gain from the feedback after each trial to choose more reasonably.

The more correct answers you give, the more bonus payment you earn. In order to count towards the bonus, responses have to be given within the time limit.

The experiment is divided into two parts. Each part consists of a seperate list of pairs.

Press any key to start with the first list.

Instructions

The aim of this experiment is to study how people learn vocabulary in a language they don't know.

In this experiment you will be presented with pairs of vocabulary from an artificial language.

Your task is to memorize which of the pairs are considered a valid pair in the artificial language.

A valid pair could look like this:

urbe tarb

An invalid pair could look like this:

urbe makt


For each pair that is presented to you, you can indicate whether or not you think it is a valid pair.

If you think it is a valid pair, press f.

If you think it is an invalid pair, press j.

After you make your choice, you will be provided with feedback.

You have 3.5 seconds to respond and the feedback will be shown for 2 seconds.

You will encounter each pair 5 times.

The first time you see each pair, you will have to guess whether it is valid or not. With time you should be able to use the knowledge you gain from the feedback after each trial to choose more reasonably.

The more correct answers you give, the more bonus payment you earn. In order to count towards the bonus, responses have to be given within the time limit.

Instructions

The aim of this experiment is to study how people learn vocabulary in a language they don't know.

In this experiment you will be presented with pairs of vocabulary from an artificial language.

Your task is to memorize which of the pairs are considered a valid pair in the artificial language.

A valid pair could look like this:

urbe tarb

An invalid pair could look like this:

urbe makt


For each pair that is presented to you, you can indicate whether or not you think it is a valid pair.

If you think it is a valid pair, press f.

If you think it is an invalid pair, press j.

After you make your choice, you will be provided with feedback.

You have 3.5 seconds to respond and the feedback will be shown for 2 seconds.

You will encounter each pair 5 times.

The first time you see each pair, you will have to guess whether it is valid or not. With time you should be able to use the knowledge you gain from the feedback after each trial to choose more reasonably.

The more correct answers you give, the more bonus payment you earn. In order to count towards the bonus, responses have to be given within the time limit.

The experiment is divided into two parts. Each part consists of a seperate list of pairs.

Press any key to start with the first list.

Instructions

The aim of this experiment is to study how people learn vocabulary in a language they don't know.

In this experiment you will be presented with pairs of vocabulary from an artificial language.

Your task is to memorize which of the pairs are considered a valid pair in the artificial language.

A valid pair could look like this:

urbe tarb

An invalid pair could look like this:

urbe makt


For each pair that is presented to you, you can indicate whether or not you think it is a valid pair.

If you think it is a valid pair, press f.

If you think it is an invalid pair, press j.

After you make your choice, you will be provided with feedback.

You have 3.5 seconds to respond and the feedback will be shown for 2 seconds.

You will encounter each pair 5 times.

The first time you see each pair, you will have to guess whether it is valid or not. With time you should be able to use the knowledge you gain from the feedback after each trial to choose more reasonably.

The more correct answers you give, the more bonus payment you earn. In order to count towards the bonus, responses have to be given within the time limit.

The experiment is divided into two parts. Each part consists of a seperate list of pairs.

Press any key to start with the first list.

Instructions

The aim of this experiment is to study how people learn vocabulary in a language they don't know.

In this experiment you will be presented with pairs of vocabulary from an artificial language.

Your task is to memorize which of the pairs are considered a valid pair in the artificial language.

A valid pair could look like this:

urbe tarb

An invalid pair could look like this:

urbe makt


For each pair that is presented to you, you can indicate whether or not you think it is a valid pair.

If you think it is a valid pair, press f.

If you think it is an invalid pair, press j.

After you make your choice, you will be provided with feedback.

You have 3.5 seconds to respond and the feedback will be shown for 2 seconds.

You will encounter each pair 5 times.

The first time you see each pair, you will have to guess whether it is valid or not. With time you should be able to use the knowledge you gain from the feedback after each trial to choose more reasonably.

The more correct answers you give, the more bonus payment you earn. In order to count towards the bonus, responses have to be given within the time limit.

The experiment is divided into two parts. Each part consists of a seperate list of pairs.

Press any key to start with the first list.

Instructions

The aim of this experiment is to study how people learn vocabulary in a language they don't know.

In this experiment you will be presented with pairs of vocabulary from an artificial language.

Your task is to memorize which of the pairs are considered a valid pair in the artificial language.

A valid pair could look like this:

urbe tarb

An invalid pair could look like this:

urbe makt


For each pair that is presented to you, you can indicate whether or not you think it is a valid pair.

If you think it is a valid pair, press f.

If you think it is an invalid pair, press j.

After you make your choice, you will be provided with feedback.

You have 3.5 seconds to respond and the feedback will be shown for 2 seconds.

You will encounter each pair 5 times.

The first time you see each pair, you will have to guess whether it is valid or not. With time you should be able to use the knowledge you gain from the feedback after each trial to choose more reasonably.

The more correct answers you give, the more bonus payment you earn. In order to count towards the bonus, responses have to be given within the time limit.

The experiment is divided into two parts. Each part consists of a seperate list of pairs.

Press any key to start with the first list.

Instructions

The aim of this experiment is to study how people learn vocabulary in a language they don't know.

In this experiment you will be presented with pairs of vocabulary from an artificial language.

Your task is to memorize which of the pairs are considered a valid pair in the artificial language.

A valid pair could look like this:

urbe tarb

An invalid pair could look like this:

urbe makt


For each pair that is presented to you, you can indicate whether or not you think it is a valid pair.

If you think it is a valid pair, press f.

If you think it is an invalid pair, press j.

After you make your choice, you will be provided with feedback.

You have 3.5 seconds to respond and the feedback will be shown for 2 seconds.

You will encounter each pair 5 times.

The first time you see each pair, you will have to guess whether it is valid or not. With time you should be able to use the knowledge you gain from the feedback after each trial to choose more reasonably.

The more correct answers you give, the more bonus payment you earn. In order to count towards the bonus, responses have to be given within the time limit.

The experiment is divided into two parts. Each part consists of a seperate list of pairs.

Press any key to start with the first list.

Instructions

The aim of this experiment is to study how people learn vocabulary in a language they don't know.

In this experiment you will be presented with pairs of vocabulary from an artificial language.

Your task is to memorize which of the pairs are considered a valid pair in the artificial language.

A valid pair could look like this:

urbe tarb

An invalid pair could look like this:

urbe makt


For each pair that is presented to you, you can indicate whether or not you think it is a valid pair.

If you think it is a valid pair, press f.

If you think it is an invalid pair, press j.

After you make your choice, you will be provided with feedback.

You have 3.5 seconds to respond and the feedback will be shown for 2 seconds.

You will encounter each pair 5 times.

The first time you see each pair, you will have to guess whether it is valid or not. With time you should be able to use the knowledge you gain from the feedback after each trial to choose more reasonably.

The more correct answers you give, the more bonus payment you earn. In order to count towards the bonus, responses have to be given within the time limit.

The experiment is divided into two parts. Each part consists of a seperate list of pairs.

Press any key to start with the first list.

Instructions

The aim of this experiment is to study how people learn vocabulary in a language they don't know.

In this experiment you will be presented with pairs of vocabulary from an artificial language.

Your task is to memorize which of the pairs are considered a valid pair in the artificial language.

A valid pair could look like this:

urbe tarb

An invalid pair could look like this:

urbe makt


For each pair that is presented to you, you can indicate whether or not you think it is a valid pair.

If you think it is a valid pair, press f.

If you think it is an invalid pair, press j.

After you make your choice, you will be provided with feedback.

You have 3.5 seconds to respond and the feedback will be shown for 2 seconds.

You will encounter each pair 5 times.

The first time you see each pair, you will have to guess whether it is valid or not. With time you should be able to use the knowledge you gain from the feedback after each trial to choose more reasonably.

The more correct answers you give, the more bonus payment you earn. In order to count towards the bonus, responses have to be given within the time limit.

The experiment is divided into two parts. Each part consists of a seperate list of pairs.

Press any key to start with the first list.

Instructions

The aim of this experiment is to study how people learn vocabulary in a language they don't know.

In this experiment you will be presented with pairs of vocabulary from an artificial language.

Your task is to memorize which of the pairs are considered a valid pair in the artificial language.

A valid pair could look like this:

urbe tarb

An invalid pair could look like this:

urbe makt


For each pair that is presented to you, you can indicate whether or not you think it is a valid pair.

If you think it is a valid pair, press f.

If you think it is an invalid pair, press j.

After you make your choice, you will be provided with feedback.

You have 3.5 seconds to respond and the feedback will be shown for 2 seconds.

You will encounter each pair 5 times.

The first time you see each pair, you will have to guess whether it is valid or not. With time you should be able to use the knowledge you gain from the feedback after each trial to choose more reasonably.

The more correct answers you give, the more bonus payment you earn. In order to count towards the bonus, responses have to be given within the time limit.

The experiment is divided into two parts. Each part consists of a seperate list of pairs.

Press any key to start with the first list.

Instructions

The aim of this experiment is to study how people learn vocabulary in a language they don't know.

In this experiment you will be presented with pairs of vocabulary from an artificial language.

Your task is to memorize which of the pairs are considered a valid pair in the artificial language.

A valid pair could look like this:

urbe tarb

An invalid pair could look like this:

urbe makt


For each pair that is presented to you, you can indicate whether or not you think it is a valid pair.

If you think it is a valid pair, press f.

If you think it is an invalid pair, press j.

After you make your choice, you will be provided with feedback.

You have 3.5 seconds to respond and the feedback will be shown for 2 seconds.

You will encounter each pair 5 times.

The first time you see each pair, you will have to guess whether it is valid or not. With time you should be able to use the knowledge you gain from the feedback after each trial to choose more reasonably.

The more correct answers you give, the more bonus payment you earn. In order to count towards the bonus, responses have to be given within the time limit.

The experiment is divided into two parts. Each part consists of a seperate list of pairs.

Press any key to start with the first list.

Instructions

The aim of this experiment is to study how people learn vocabulary in a language they don't know.

In this experiment you will be presented with pairs of vocabulary from an artificial language.

Your task is to memorize which of the pairs are considered a valid pair in the artificial language.

A valid pair could look like this:

urbe tarb

An invalid pair could look like this:

urbe makt


For each pair that is presented to you, you can indicate whether or not you think it is a valid pair.

If you think it is a valid pair, press f.

If you think it is an invalid pair, press j.

After you make your choice, you will be provided with feedback.

You have 3.5 seconds to respond and the feedback will be shown for 2 seconds.

You will encounter each pair 5 times.

The first time you see each pair, you will have to guess whether it is valid or not. With time you should be able to use the knowledge you gain from the feedback after each trial to choose more reasonably.

The more correct answers you give, the more bonus payment you earn. In order to count towards the bonus, responses have to be given within the time limit.

The experiment is divided into two parts. Each part consists of a seperate list of pairs.

Press any key to start with the first list.

Instructions

The aim of this experiment is to study how people learn vocabulary in a language they don't know.

In this experiment you will be presented with pairs of vocabulary from an artificial language.

Your task is to memorize which of the pairs are considered a valid pair in the artificial language.

A valid pair could look like this:

urbe tarb

An invalid pair could look like this:

urbe makt


For each pair that is presented to you, you can indicate whether or not you think it is a valid pair.

If you think it is a valid pair, press f.

If you think it is an invalid pair, press j.

After you make your choice, you will be provided with feedback.

You have 3.5 seconds to respond and the feedback will be shown for 2 seconds.

You will encounter each pair 5 times.

The first time you see each pair, you will have to guess whether it is valid or not. With time you should be able to use the knowledge you gain from the feedback after each trial to choose more reasonably.

The more correct answers you give, the more bonus payment you earn. In order to count towards the bonus, responses have to be given within the time limit.

The experiment is divided into two parts. Each part consists of a seperate list of pairs.

Press any key to start with the first list.
